{"_id":"20173fb0-d8ef-11eb-b968-d76a3395ed13","postId":"2009_05_detection-of-half-open-dropped-f127b1d1-2c83-3dd0-9e4b-214360c6e878","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2009/05/detection-of-half-open-dropped.html","replyTo":"41b22bb0-d0d1-11eb-a8a5-1795105e7292","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"That really depends. If the network is truly down (no link), then you'll get an error reported back on your next read. If there's another network path, then the connection is maintained and the data is delivered normally. If the network cable is unplugged directly from the computer and the computer is running Windows, then you'll get an error reported back immediately.","date":"2021-06-29T15:31:51.456Z"}